        {
          "title": "Distributed Application Architectures",
          "type": "instruction",
          "path": "instruction/distributed-application-architectures/distributed-application-architectures.md",
          "id": "55fcd10b-d313-4f56-b69b-7608d05242cf",
          "state": "published",
          "interactions": [
            "2c6e844f-d498-44ef-8ac3-2a25b99d7b34"
          ],
          "description": "This topic discusses five popular different distributed application architectures. They are compared and contrasted with coding examples and  UML dataflow diagrams for each. \n\nOther architectures are also mentioned.\n\n\nArchitecture Model\tDescription\tAdvantages\tDisadvantages\tCommon Examples\nClient-Server\tClients request services from centralized servers.\tSimple, easy to manage.\tServer can become a bottleneck or single point of failure.\tWeb applications, email systems\nThree-Tier Architecture\tPresentation, business logic, and data layers are separated.\tBetter maintainability and scalability.\tMore complexity than client-server.\tEnterprise applications\nN-Tier (Multi-Tier)\tMultiple layers for presentation, services, business logic, and data.\tHigh scalability and separation of concerns.\tIncreased deployment complexity.\tLarge enterprise systems\nPeer-to-Peer (P2P)\tEvery node acts as both client and server.\tHighly decentralized and fault tolerant.\tDifficult coordination and security.\tBitTorrent, blockchain networks\nService-Oriented Architecture (SOA)\tBusiness functions exposed as reusable services.\tReusability and enterprise integration.\tHeavy infrastructure and governance.\tEnterprise integration systems\nMicroservices Architecture\tApplication divided into small independently deployable services.\tScalability, independent deployments.\tDistributed system complexity.\tNetflix, Amazon, Uber\nEvent-Driven Architecture (EDA)\tComponents communicate through events.\tLoose coupling, highly scalable.\tDebugging and tracing can be difficult.\tIoT systems, real-time analytics\nMessage-Oriented Architecture\tComponents exchange messages through queues or brokers.\tReliability and asynchronous processing.\tIncreased latency and operational complexity.\tRabbitMQ, ActiveMQ systems\nServerless Architecture\tFunctions execute in response to events and are managed by cloud providers.\tNo server management, pay-per-use.\tVendor lock-in and cold starts.\tAWS Lambda, Azure Functions\nSpace-Based Architecture\tData and processing distributed across memory grids to eliminate database bottlenecks.\tHigh throughput and elasticity.\tComplex design and data consistency challenges.\tHigh-volume e-commerce platforms\nDistributed Object Architecture\tObjects communicate across network boundaries.\tNatural object-oriented design.\tTight coupling and scalability issues.\tCORBA, Java RMI\nActor Model Architecture\tIndependent actors communicate via asynchronous messages.\tExcellent concurrency and fault isolation.\tDifferent programming paradigm.\tErlang/OTP, Akka\nCQRS + Event Sourcing\tSeparate read and write models; state reconstructed from events.\tScalability, auditability.\tHigh complexity.\tFinancial systems, auditing platforms\nData-Centric Architecture\tShared distributed data store is the central integration point.\tSimplifies data sharing.\tCan create contention around data store.\tDistributed databases, data lakes\n"
        },
